00:18:36,060 --> 00:18:40,940
Sarasti was the official intermediary. When the ship did speak, it spoke to him,

227
00:18:40,940 --> 00:18:48,420
and Sarasti called it captain. So did we all. He'd given us four hours to come back.

228
00:18:48,460 --> 00:18:55,020
It took more than three just to get me out of the crypt. By then, my brain was at least firing on most of its synapses,

229
00:18:55,020 --> 00:18:59,540
although my body, still sucking fluids like a thirsty sponge, continued to ache

230
00:18:59,540 --> 00:19:03,980
with every movement. I swapped out drained electrolyte bags or fresh ones and headed

231
00:19:03,980 --> 00:19:10,180
aft. Fifteen minutes to spin up. Fifty to the post-Raz briefing. Just enough time

232
00:19:10,180 --> 00:19:13,500
for those who preferred gravity bow and sleep to haul their personal effects

233
00:19:13,620 --> 00:19:17,740
into the drum and stake out their allotted 4.4 square meters of floor space.

234
00:19:17,740 --> 00:19:24,340
Gravity, or any centripetal facsimile thereof, did not appeal to me. I set up my

235
00:19:24,340 --> 00:19:28,700
own tent in zero G in as far as Stern as possible, nuzzling the forward wall of the

236
00:19:28,700 --> 00:19:33,780
starboard shuttle tube. The tent inflated like an abscess on Theesius's spine, a

237
00:19:33,780 --> 00:19:37,620
little climate-controlled bubble of atmosphere in the dark cavernous vacuum

238
00:19:37,620 --> 00:19:42,380
beneath the ship's carapace. My own effects were minimal. It took all of 30

239
00:19:42,420 --> 00:19:45,580
seconds to stick them to the wall and another 30 to program the tent's

240
00:19:45,580 --> 00:19:50,740
environment. Afterwards, I went for a hike. After five years, I needed the

241
00:19:50,740 --> 00:19:55,780
exercise. Stern was closest, so I started there, at the shielding that separated

242
00:19:55,780 --> 00:20:00,140
payload from propulsion. A single sealed hatch blistered the aft bulkhead dead

243
00:20:00,140 --> 00:20:04,340
center. Behind it, a service tunnel warmed back through the machinery best left

244
00:20:04,340 --> 00:20:08,580
untouched by human hands. The fat, superconducting torus of the ram scoop

245
00:20:08,620 --> 00:20:12,860
ring. The antennae fan behind it unwound now into an indestructible soap bubble

246
00:20:12,860 --> 00:20:16,660
big enough to shroud a city. Its face turned sunward to catch the faint

247
00:20:16,660 --> 00:20:21,100
quantum sparkle of the aqueous antimatter stream. More shielding behind

248
00:20:21,100 --> 00:20:25,300
that than the telematter reactor, where raw hydrogen and refined information

249
00:20:25,300 --> 00:20:30,940
conjured fire 300 times hotter than the sun's. I knew the incantations, of

250
00:20:30,940 --> 00:20:34,660
course, antimatter cracking and deconstruction, the teleportation of

251
00:20:34,700 --> 00:20:39,060
quantum serial numbers, but it was still magic to me how we'd come so far so

252
00:20:39,060 --> 00:20:46,100
fast. It would have been magic to anyone, except Sarasti, maybe. Around me, the same

253
00:20:46,100 --> 00:20:50,580
magic worked at cooler temperatures and to less volatile ends. A small riot of

254
00:20:50,580 --> 00:20:54,940
shoots and dispensers crowded the bulkhead on all sides. A few of those

255
00:20:54,940 --> 00:20:59,380
openings would choke on my fist. One or two could swallow me whole. The easiest

256
00:20:59,380 --> 00:21:03,700
fabrication plant could build everything from cutlery to cockpits, give it a big

257
00:21:03,740 --> 00:21:07,260
enough matter stockpile and it could even have built another thesias, albeit in

258
00:21:07,260 --> 00:21:11,940
many small pieces and over a very long time. Some wondered if it could build

259
00:21:11,940 --> 00:21:16,420
another crew as well, although we'd been assured that was impossible. Not even

260
00:21:16,420 --> 00:21:20,660
these machines had fine enough fingers to reconstruct a few trillion SNAT synapses

261
00:21:20,660 --> 00:21:27,020
in the space of the human skull. Not yet, anyway. I believed it. They would never

262
00:21:27,020 --> 00:21:30,980
have shipped us out fully assembled if there had been a cheaper alternative. I

263
00:21:31,020 --> 00:21:35,180
faced forward. Putting the back of my head against that sealed hatch, I could see

264
00:21:35,180 --> 00:21:40,060
almost a thesias' bow, an uninterrupted line of sight extending to a tiny dark

265
00:21:40,060 --> 00:21:44,580
bullseye 30 meters ahead. It was like staring at a great textured target in

266
00:21:44,580 --> 00:21:48,020
shades of white and gray, concentric circles, hatches centered within

267
00:21:48,020 --> 00:21:52,340
bulkheads one behind another, perfectly aligned. Every once stood open in

268
00:21:52,340 --> 00:21:56,700
non-schlot defiance of a previous generation's safety codes. We could keep

269
00:21:56,700 --> 00:22:00,940
them closed if we wanted to, if it made us feel safer. That was all it would do

270
00:22:00,940 --> 00:22:05,380
though. It wouldn't improve our Imperial odds one bit. In the event of trouble,

271
00:22:05,380 --> 00:22:09,140
those hatches would slam shut milliseconds before human senses could even make

272
00:22:09,140 --> 00:22:14,020
sense of an alarm. They weren't even computer controlled. The easiest body

